english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Pure Heart
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Kang of Jinju entered the palace in his youth and served King Gongmin for decades, earning renown for his integrity and careful conduct. Later, devoted to the Buddha's way, he purified his heart and abstained from pungent vegetables and meat for another ten years and more. When the present sovereign ascended the throne, bringing clarity to both court and realm, he carefully selected worthy eunuchs for the imperial guard. Master Kang, distinguished by his incorruptible character, was appointed to serve in the inner palace. Whenever sacred incense was offered or blessings pronounced, the sovereign entrusted these duties to him alone. Master Kang maintained his ritual purity with ever greater care, dedicating himself wholly to these sacred acts. Thus the favor of both the king and queen grew day by day. Yet Master Kang remained ever humble and frugal, never displaying a trace of arrogance. In his residence, he maintained a single room of absolute cleanliness, burning incense there daily. Upon leaving the palace, he would sit in stillness, gathering his spirit and casting away the ten thousand distractions of the world. Worldly gain held no sway over him. It was thus he named his hall the "Hall of Pure Heart," and many learned scholars and Buddhist monks composed verses in praise and admiration.

    He has asked me to write this record. I reflect that the human heart is the source of all spiritual power—it participates in the harmony of heaven, earth, and humanity, encompasses all principles, and responds to all circumstances. When we cultivate its goodness, we walk the path of the sages. When we follow mere desire, we differ little from beasts. The difference lies only in a single thought. Mencius taught: "There is no better way to nurture the heart than to diminish desire." When one can diminish desire, the heart naturally becomes clear. When the heart is clear, all goodness springs forth. At the utmost clarity, the mind becomes luminous and transparent—human desire is purified and Heaven's principle operates. The virtue of the sages becomes attainable. Yet if a single unwholesome thought takes root in the heart and is not dispelled, it clouds the vast sky like dark mist, or muddies the clear stream like turbid water. The eye craves color, the mouth craves taste, and our mind's clarity dims day by day. Selfish desires and scheming thoughts swarm and flourish—we become scarcely distinguishable from beasts. Is diminishing desire not therefore the essential key to purifying the heart? Master Kang has already practiced this discipline upon himself. Let him continue and deepen this effort all the more.

    Written in the summer, fifth month of the Hongwu era, year Bingzi.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mencius (372-289 BCE): The quote references Mencius 7B35, a foundational text in Neo-Confucian thought about moral cultivation.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Three talents (三才): A cosmological concept referring to heaven, earth, and humanity as the three fundamental dimensions of existence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Human desire versus Heaven''s principle (人欲/天理): A key Neo-Confucian distinction between selfish impulses and the natural moral order of the universe.'
